Hi Curt and the other distinguished members of the list:

Well, I finally got some disk space freed up on my dying toy here, and got a
look at the screen shots of ACM.

Very nice.  I found the graphics to be better than what you claimed for FS4,
and better than Falcon.  It reminded me somwhat of Tornado.  I can
understand Riley's lack of a panel, since in a combat sim of this nature,
you concentrate on the HUD anyway, since it displays all the pertinent data
for your mission at hand.  I presume the rectangles on the panel are
annunciator lights for warning/failures.

I really feel that your proposal should be seriously undertaken, as I think
ACM could serve as an excelent base to build upon.  The good thing is that
it uses the TCP/IP stack for multi-user play, so this should fit in very
nicely for internet dual player etc.  I do not see this protocol going away
for a long time (the industry said the same thing about X.25, and it is
still around!)

As far as my comments about porting to other platforms, I also checked your
link to the ACM site, and saw that it runs on most of the OS's I mentioned,
so again, this reinforces my belief in my prior statement.

Please be aware that although I use to code, I have not coded in years.  I
can imagine the effort that would be required to build on existing code, but
I honestly believe that for the development team on this project, it could
save you a significant amount of time, and maybe put us in a position to
have a working program in 8 to 14 months?

Lets get going, as I'm itching to get the FDE's working and write the DOCS.

Now, if I could only get a toy that I could run Linux on, the compilers
required and check the program out further.

BTW Curt, I like the picture of the mascot!  What IQ does he have? :-)

