Curt,

Let me address a couple of concerns based principally on the questions of
broad-based usability. In the world of communications (technical or
otherwise) the first question that must always be asked is: "Who is my
probable target audience." This is also the first question that a marketing
analyst must ask when considering the development of a new product.

Developing for the broadest possible user base does not equate to designing
to the lowest common denominator. A minimal equipment/performance baseline
must be established at a high enough level to guarantee a truly superior
high-fidelity product. Obviously, the highest that we might aspire to would
a mega multi-user international system powered by a couple of Crays.
Impractical? Yeah, probably. 

How about a slightly-less-than-mega multi-user system based on Sun or Unix
systems? For the long haul, definitely. For the short term, I'm afraid
(though I'd love to be proved wrong on this one) that it's impractical
except for limited and localized applications. State of the art just isn't
there yet for the industry on an affordable, Internet-wide basis. Too narrow
on the readily-available bandwidth; too broad on the communications costs.
That leaves only intranet usage.

My own conviction on this then is that, for the present, FG's best hope for
broad enough acceptance to make it worth the effort lies in developing the
very best product that can be used as a single-player sim on a PC, while
also allowing (through OOAP) sufficiently portability to make it possible to
use it in a multi-user environment.

Where does this leave us with respect to ACM? 
IF the existing code development is truly superior to anything else that
might be made available to us as a starting point, *and*
IF that code can be *easily* reworked for PC (but not necessarily DOS)
applications.
THEN it might make an acceptable (maybe even great) launching pad.
IF NOT, then the code fiddling necessary to "make it fit" might require as
much effort as starting from scratch and building a more developer-friendly
platform. And even if we did succeed in "making it fit", we might wind up
with something less functional that what the extra "from scratch" effort
might have produced. 

Of course trade-offs will be necessary. A major constraint that we will have
to be guided by is available time of the participants. But why not start by
defining the absolute best that we *might* be able to achieve if all of the
conditions were just right, and then step back from there to the highest
acceptable compromise. 

Bottom Line: Has someone else already created a superior development
paradigm that we can use to achieve our highest objectives? If not, are we
willing to take on the task of redefining the whole paradigm of simming as
it applies to private and commercial aircraft?

The (operational) mission statement of the US Navy might be summed up in one
dictum: Put ordnance on the target IN SUPPORT OF THE MISSION.

What is the FG mission? Well, that has yet to be declared, but I'll throw in
my own candidate:
========================
To create the best high-fidelity civil/commercial flight simulation possible
for use by the general simming community. It should offer power simmers a
truly realistic experience while also offering casual simmers an opportunity
to enter at a level appropriate to their abilities and progress as far as
they desire.
========================

But a mission statement must be defined an accepted up front. Only then can
practical decisions about platforms, code development, etc. be made. And
each decisions must be made IN SUPPORT OF THE MISSION.

Well, I'm not really offering many answers. Just a bunch of new questions.
But as I once mentioned to Dave, one of my favorite roles is that of devil's
advocate. Hope you don't find that too obnoxious.

Shalom,

Shmuel
