Curtis and all,

I was just thinking about MS's announcement that they will not be releasing
an FShop-type program with FSFW95, and it gave me an idea. What if, instead
of a full-blown sim engine, the FG group concentrated on a shorter-range
(for now, at least) project of producing a Win95 compatible design engine.
Much of the R&D needed to create the entire app would apply also to an
aircraft/scenery/ATC design package capable of creating component add-ons,
instrument add-ons (HSI, GPS, etc), adventure add-ons and so forth. But it
could be done more quickly.

It would be good to get the Win95 "icon of approval", but even without it,
such a package would go a long way toward sparking increased interest in the
more advanced aspects of simming. I don't remember MS ever giving approving
any freeware of shareware apps, but that's not to say that they might not if
the circumstances warranted it. 

If we could get the go-ahead from MS as a legitimate Windows-app design
team, then we could handle code compatibility in a straightforward fashion,
instead of with a series of workarounds. The thing would actually be
DESIGNED to operate efficiently alongside what, for better or worse, is
destined to become one of, if not the, most popular sim products on the
market. And this could always, if circumstances warranted, become just a
stepping stone to development of a complete stand-alone package.

Any ideas on this?

Shalom,
Shmuel

