Dave,

>So, why would
>we need an app like this, if we're able to use the old FSFS?
>For the sake of making a better interface or what not?
>
>Just curious?? :)
>Dave

Principally because it would be better to have a design package that was
BUILT to operate alongside the main sim engine, rather than one that can
create compatible add-ons only through the use of a converter (which will
probably cost something in terms of performance). FSFS is okay for designing
16-bit stuff, but I'm pretty sure that only true 32-bit coding will be able
to make the grade after a while.

It's kind of like using scenery designed for FS4 with the 5.1 engine. Of
course we *can*, but how many of us *do*. Why not? It just doesn't make the
grade. Will 5.1 quality add-ons be the end of the line? I don't think so.

Dean added:
>On another note, Win95 game-development is slightly proprietary at 
>the moment, with all the Games SDK and DirectX development tools and 
>source that you need to license from MS. Kinda prevents the little 
>guy from coming up with anything, unless they reinvent DirectX.

Licensing costs would present a problem. Question is, since this community
already has a reputation for turning out some good quality material, would
it be in MSs best interest to help us develop the tool that could perpetuate
that? If they intended to develop their own design package then obviously
not. But since they don't...

If a team of airline professionals, programers, applications development
specialists, etc. went to MS with some of the best examples of what this
group has designed in the last year and promised a continual flow of product
designed to work just as well with Win95 and beyond if they will just help
us to produce the design package and allow it to be freely distributed,
would they be interested? Maybe not. Then again.

Shmuel

